<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">The role of brick-and-mortar stores has rapidly evolved over the past few years. Despite the speed and convenience of online retail, people still crave the in-store experience &mdash; visiting physical stores lets customers ask questions, seek support, and browse products in a way online can't replicate.</p>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">Brands have to be able to capitalise on this appetite effectively. Today's stores must offer connected omnichannel services that deliver immersive, seamless in-store shopping experiences, and deploy the latest technologies that let in-store associates take care of visitors and cater to their individual needs.</p>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">According to the UK Omnichannel Retail report, 61% of consumers still favour in-store shopping, while 39% shop mostly online. With the rising cost of living making many shoppers mindful of wasteful spending, a number of online-first brands, such as Gymshark and Manière De Voir, have expanded into brick-and-mortar with pop-ups and permanent store placements.</p>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">The increase in customers heading back to stores has led shop owners to turn to retail technology to modernise in-store experiences, utilising tools such as radio frequency identification (RFID) and mobile point of sale (POS) to optimise sales opportunities and free up in-store staff to focus on the customer. But to bring the excitement back to in-store shopping, retailers must go further and create genuinely engaging ways to reach customers in 2025.</p>

<h2>The In-Store Popularity Complex</h2>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">A recent Statista study found that by the end of 2024, only 26.5% of UK retail sales came from internet purchases. With nearly three-quarters of transactions taking place in-store in the build-up to the festive season &mdash; the busiest shopping period of the year &mdash; it's clear consumers still prefer shopping in-store.</p>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">But while consumers might be flocking to the high street for a high-quality in-store experience, a busy, chaotic shop floor can cause frustration, queuing, and a fragmented customer journey &mdash; the opposite of what an in-store visit is supposed to deliver.</p>

<h2>Delivering High-Quality Experiences on a Busy Shop Floor</h2>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">Technology plays a pivotal role in delivering on that experiential promise. By equipping in-store staff with the right tools, retailers can let their sales floor team work efficiently while delivering personalised customer experiences that leave shoppers feeling valued.</p>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">The point of sale is one of the most crucial touchpoints in the retail journey and often the final opportunity to deliver a high-quality experience, which makes seamless, fast transactions essential. Evolving the self-checkout experience gives customers autonomy, and when integrated with RFID &mdash; where readers automatically scan every item in a basket at once &mdash; in-store visitors can complete transactions in under 30 seconds. A frictionless checkout helps retailers deliver real customer satisfaction while actively reducing shop floor queuing.</p>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">High-quality customer service can go one step further with mobile POS devices, letting customers complete transactions anywhere in-store and eliminating the need to queue at all. Operating from a tablet or mobile device, retailers can integrate wider operational technologies &mdash; CRM, order management, and inventory management &mdash; to leverage accurate data that powers personalised experiences.</p>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">Shop staff can use purchase history and customer preferences to make specific product recommendations, conduct buy online, pick-up in-store (BOPIS) transactions, process returns, and give customers accurate product availability and location information. On a busy shop floor, this all-encompassing approach to retail technology equips in-store staff with the knowledge to deliver services tailored to the individual customer &mdash; and to do all of it before completing a transaction on the spot.</p>

<h2>Modernising the Customer Shopping Experience</h2>
<p style="color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">Brick-and-mortar retail is thriving. By taking a modernised approach to the in-store experience &mdash; leveraging technology to empower shop floor associates to deliver the best possible experience &mdash; retailers can drive high customer satisfaction in the short term and increase customer loyalty and retention over the long term.</p>
